  "text": "While potential complications of epidural analgesia such as epidural haematoma or abscess formation and their associated neurological sequelae can be debilitating, they are fortunately extremely rare. [CITATION_1] As postoperative coagulopathy can be commonly seen following liver resection, the advantages have to be carefully balanced against the risks of epidural catheter placement and removal. [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] The aim of our study was to analyse the success rates and complications of epidural analgesia in liver resections performed with a standardised bilateral subcostal incision without a midline component. We also aimed at identifying any correlation between epidural failure, duration of stay and complications (chest infection and wound infection).",
